<p><i><b>Altered States</b></i> is a <a href="/wiki/1980_in_film" title="1980 in film">1980</a> <a href="/wiki/Science_fiction" title="Science fiction">science fiction</a> <a href="/wiki/Film_adaptation" title="Film adaptation">film adaptation</a> of a novel by the same name by playwright and screenwriter <a href="/wiki/Paddy_Chayefsky" title="Paddy Chayefsky">Paddy Chayefsky</a>. It was the only novel that Chayefsky ever wrote, as well as his final film. Both the novel and the film are based on <a href="/wiki/John_C._Lilly" title="John C. Lilly">John C. Lilly</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Sensory_deprivation" title="Sensory deprivation">sensory deprivation</a> research conducted in <a href="/wiki/Isolation_tank" title="Isolation tank">isolation tanks</a> under the influence of <a href="/wiki/Psychoactive_drugs" title="Psychoactive drugs" class="mw-redirect">psychoactive drugs</a> like <a href="/wiki/Ketamine" title="Ketamine">ketamine</a> and <a href="/wiki/LSD" title="LSD" class="mw-redirect">LSD</a>.</p>
<p>The film was directed by <a href="/wiki/Ken_Russell" title="Ken Russell">Ken Russell</a> and starred <a href="/wiki/William_Hurt" title="William Hurt">William Hurt</a> in his screen debut. It also starred <a href="/wiki/Blair_Brown" title="Blair Brown">Blair Brown</a> (as <a href="/wiki/Emily_Jessup" title="Emily Jessup">Emily Jessup</a>), <a href="/wiki/Charles_Haid" title="Charles Haid">Charles Haid</a> and <a href="/wiki/Bob_Balaban" title="Bob Balaban">Bob Balaban</a>. It additionally featured the film debut of <a href="/wiki/Drew_Barrymore" title="Drew Barrymore">Drew Barrymore</a>. The <a href="/wiki/Film_score" title="Film score">film score</a> was composed by classical composer <a href="/wiki/John_Corigliano" title="John Corigliano">John Corigliano</a> (with <a href="/wiki/Christopher_Keene" title="Christopher Keene">Christopher Keene</a> conducting) and was <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Original_Music_Score#1980s" title="Academy Award for Original Music Score" class="mw-redirect">nominated for an Academy Award</a>. The film also received an <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Sound#1980s" title="Academy Award for Sound" class="mw-redirect">Oscar nomination for Sound</a>, losing to <i><a href="/wiki/The_Empire_Strikes_Back" title="The Empire Strikes Back" class="mw-redirect">The Empire Strikes Back</a></i>.</p>
